            <sec sec-type="bodytext" indexed="true">
               <title/>
               <p>The Magna Carta, or Great Charter, was one of the first documents in the history of Western civilization to acknowledge individual liberties. Drafted by English nobility and sealed by <related-article xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
                                   related-article-type="rs"
                                   xlink:href="92667795"
                                   xlink:type="simple">King John</related-article> under threat of revolt, the document gave credence to the notion of human rights and the obligation of a government to its citizens. Although initially concerned with relationships between the king, his lords, and clerics, the provisions of the charter took on greater significance as feudal rights were extended to all English citizens. Thus the article requiring new taxes to be approved by a council of nobles resulted in the creation of the English Parliament, and the clause prohibiting the punishment of a lord “except by the legal judgment of his peers or the law of the land” gave rise to the legal concepts of due process and trial by jury.<index-term>
                     <primary>[cat]CIVIL RIGHTS AND LIBERTIES;Magna Carta</primary>
                  </index-term>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>[cat]CONSTITUTIONAL PROTECTIONS;Magna Carta</primary>
                  </index-term>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>[cat]POLITICAL ISSUES;Magna Carta</primary>
                  </index-term>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>[a]Magna Carta</primary>
                  </index-term>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>Civil liberties;and Magna Carta[Magna Carta]</primary>
                  </index-term>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>[p]John, King</primary>
                  </index-term>
               </p>
               <fig fig-type="elec_use" position="margin">
                  <caption>
                     <title>A Chronicle of England - Page 226 - John Signs the Great Charter</title>
                     <p>King John signs the Magna Carta.</p>
                  </caption>
                  <ext-link xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
                            ext-link-type="db-image"
                            xlink:href="87323589-107576.jpg"
                            xlink:type="simple"/>
                  <permissions>
                     <copyright-statement>James William Edmund Doyle [Public domain], via Wikimedia Commons</copyright-statement>
                  </permissions>
               </fig>
               <fig fig-type="elec_use" position="margin">
                  <caption>
                     <title>ABA-wyrdlight-815935</title>
                     <p>The Magna Carta Memorial at Runnymede, designed by Sir Edward Maufe and erected by the American Bar Association in 1957. The memorial stands in the meadow known historically as Long Mede</p>
                  </caption>
                  <ext-link xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
                            ext-link-type="db-image"
                            xlink:href="87323589-107577.jpg"
                            xlink:type="simple"/>
                  <permissions>
                     <copyright-statement>WyrdLight.com [CC BY-SA 4.0 (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0) or CC BY-SA 4.0 (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0)], via Wikimedia Commons</copyright-statement>
                  </permissions>
               </fig>
               <p>The legacy of the Magna Carta passed down through English common law to become an integral part of the legal system and governmental structure of the United States. The <related-article xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
                                   related-article-type="rs"
                                   xlink:href="98402225"
                                   xlink:type="simple">US Congress</related-article> was modeled on the bicameral British Parliament, and many of the provisions of the <related-article xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
                                   related-article-type="rs"
                                   xlink:href="89402598"
                                   xlink:type="simple">Bill of Rights</related-article> and the <related-article xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
                                   related-article-type="rs"
                                   xlink:href="89402401"
                                   xlink:type="simple">Fourteenth amendment</related-article> to the US Constitution, such as the right to due process, trial by jury, and <italic>habeas corpus</italic>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>
                        <italic>Habeas corpus</italic>;and Magna Carta[Magna Carta]</primary>
                  </index-term> can be traced back to the Magna Carta.<index-term>
                     <primary>[a]Magna Carta</primary>
                  </index-term>
                  <index-term>
                     <primary>Civil liberties;and Magna Carta[Magna Carta]</primary>
                  </index-term>
               </p>
